Edition:
Quote: <i>second cut NZ & Austral.</i> second blow made to remove badly cut fleece, inferior piece of wool resulting from this.
Notes:  [nf. 1982 Collins Concise Eng. Dict.]

Date: 0/0/1986
Source: NZ Pocket Oxford Dictionary
Author:
Vol / Page: 688
Edition:
Quote: <i>second cut NZ & Austral.</i> second blow made to remove badly cut fleece, inferior piece of wool resulting from this.
Notes:  [nf. 1982 Collins Concise Eng. Dict.]

Date: 0/0/1989
Source: NZ English Newsletter
Author:
Vol / Page: 3/27
Edition:
Quote: <i>second cut</i>: This results when the shears are allowed to move off the sheep's skin and so into the fleece, making another blow necessary. Second cuts spoil the fleece and are said to cost the wool industry millions of dollars a year. This is because the second cut of prime wool is downgraded to the price of locks, and the main fleece brings a lower price because of its uneven staple length.
Notes: (Wallace Shearing Glossary)
